### What is the API Gateway?

The API Gateway is the platform's standard ingress layer for exposing services over HTTP and HTTPS.

It combines Kubernetes Gateway API resources with Envoy data plane instances to provide consistent routing, TLS termination, and safer service exposure patterns across clusters.

The supporting infrastructure and controller components are managed through Terraform so configuration is repeatable between environments.

### How API Gateway Works

The API Gateway provides a single entry point for traffic coming into the platform and routes requests to the correct service inside the cluster.

At a high level, the flow is:

1. A user sends a request to a public hostname.
2. External-DNS keeps that hostname pointed at the load balancer created for Envoy.
3. Envoy Gateway receives the request and evaluates Gateway API resources (for example, `Gateway` and `HTTPRoute`) to decide where to send it.
4. The request is forwarded to the matching Kubernetes `Service` in the target namespace.
5. The service sends traffic to healthy application pods.

TLS certificates are issued and renewed by cert-manager, so HTTPS is terminated securely at the gateway.

This model gives teams a consistent, declarative way to publish services while keeping routing, TLS, and DNS management centralised.


### Envoy

The Envoy component deploys and manages only the Envoy system in the cluster.

The [container-platform-terraform-envoy-gateway](https://github.com/ministryofjustice/container-platform-terraform-envoy-gateway) repository provisions and configures the Envoy Gateway deployment.

In practice, Envoy is responsible for:

1. Accepting inbound HTTP/HTTPS requests.
2. Matching requests to configured routes.
3. Forwarding requests to the correct Kubernetes services.
4. Returning upstream responses to clients.

### Gateway

The Gateway API defines how teams publish applications using Kubernetes-native resources such as `Gateway`, `HTTPRoute`, and related policy objects.

The [container-platform-terraform-gateway-api](https://github.com/ministryofjustice/container-platform-terraform-gateway-api) repository manages installation and baseline configuration for these Gateway API components so routing behaviour is consistent across clusters.

The Gateway component is also responsible for deploying the external load balancer used to receive inbound traffic.

This gives service teams a declarative interface for traffic management while the platform team controls shared guardrails and defaults.

### Cert-Manager

cert-manager automates certificate lifecycle management for gateway hostnames, including issuance and renewal.

The [container-platform-terraform-cert-manager](https://github.com/ministryofjustice/container-platform-terraform-cert-manager) repository manages the cert-manager installation and related cluster configuration used by the gateway stack.

By integrating cert-manager with Gateway resources, HTTPS can be enabled without manual certificate handling for each service.

### External-DNS

External-DNS keeps DNS records aligned with gateway endpoints so public hostnames resolve to the correct load balancer.

The [container-platform-terraform-external-dns](https://github.com/ministryofjustice/container-platform-terraform-external-dns) repository provisions and configures External-DNS for this automation.

When gateway endpoints or host definitions change, External-DNS updates records automatically, reducing manual DNS operations and drift.

